{"\ufeffThe Journey of a Notebook\nStories of Impact \u00b7 June 2026\nReading time: 9 minutes\n________________\n\n\nI. Discarded\nThe notebook cost four hundred and eighty rupees.\nIt was the kind that came in a kraft paper sleeve, with a subtle grid pattern on the covers and pages that were thick enough that a fountain pen did not bleed through to the other side. Aryan had picked it from the stationery section of a mall in Bandra, attracted by the aesthetic \u2014 the clean spine, the elastic band closure, the ribbon bookmark in forest green.\nHe had used it for his Class 11 economics notes. September through November. Forty-one pages, front and back, covered in his handwriting \u2014 the careful, slightly performative handwriting of a teenager who had watched too many journaling videos and wanted his notes to look like the ones in them.\nAnd then the chapter had changed. The teacher had moved to a topic that required graphs and diagrams that did not suit the grid pages. He had started a new notebook \u2014 a plain one from the college bookshop, \u20b935, suited to graphs. The economics notebook had moved to the edge of his study desk.\nThen behind the desk lamp.\nThen into the bottom drawer with the warranties and the dead pens.\nIn March, his mother had declared a clean-up. The notebook, along with a tower of textbooks, a defunctlaptop sleeve, three empty cardboard boxes, and a bag of old magazines, had been carried to the front of the building and left in a neat pile outside the gate.\nThe pile sat in the morning light.\nThe notebook sat on top of it, its elastic band still holding, its cover still clean, its last forty-one pages still completely, perfectly blank.\nIt had been used for fifty-eight days.\nIt had 141 unused pages.\nIt was, by every reasonable measure, not finished.\n________________\n\n\nII. Collected\nSalim Chacha came down the lane at 7:40 AM.\nHe had been doing this route for nineteen years. The same lanes, the same buildings, the same rhythm \u2014 the metal trolley, the weighing scale hanging from its hook, the call that every child in every building in this part of Mumbai could imitate. Raddi-wallaaaa. Kabaad-wallaaaa.\nHe had an eye for things. Not just for weight \u2014 for potential. For the difference between paper that was uniformly printed on both sides and paper that still had room for something. His sorting happened faster than it looked. A glance. A thumb through the pages. A category assigned.\nHe picked up the notebook from the top of the pile.\nOpened it. Riffled from the back.\nBlank. Blank. Blank. Blank. Forty pages at least, maybe more.\nHe set it in the section of his trolley where he kept things that were not pure raddi. The things that needed to go to Meena Didi's place, not to the paper recycler.\nMeena Didi ran a sorting operation out of a single-room space in Dharavi. The room was impossible \u2014 shelves from floor to ceiling, crates, bags, a weighing scale in the corner, a ceiling fan that had not been fully balanced since 2018 and made a sound like a slow helicopter. It smelled of paper and rubber bands and the particular dustiness of collected things.\nSalim Chacha came twice a week.\nHe placed the notebook on the counter.\nMeena Didi opened it, checked it, held it up to the light from the window.\n\"Accha hai,\" she said, quietly, to nobody in particular. Good one.\nIt went into the pile on the second shelf from the top.\n________________\n\n\nIII. Remade\nThe NGO was called Doosra Mauka \u2014 Second Chance.\nIt was run by a woman named Fatima Shaikh from a rented space in Kurla, with eleven trained volunteers and a annual budget that would not cover three months of operating costs for most mid-sized companies. She had started it seven years earlier because she had a specific, granular understanding of a specific, granular problem:\nRural government schools in Maharashtra were perpetually short of notebooks.\nNot all notebooks. Specifically, blank-page notebooks for practice. Exercises. Rough work. Drafts.\nThe government provided textbooks. It sometimes provided one or two subject notebooks. But the notebooks children needed to actually learn \u2014 to write and rewrite and practise and make mistakes and try again \u2014 those were perpetually, consistently, infuriatingly in short supply.\nFatima had started collecting surplus notebooks from the city and having the blank pages rebound.\nHer volunteers had a process. Notebooks like Aryan's \u2014 with used pages at the front and blank pages at the back \u2014 were opened to the first blank page, the binding was carefully cut, and the blank section was separated. These sections were gathered, sorted by size, aligned, punched, and bound with recycled card covers using a hand-operated binding machine that Fatima had found secondhand and maintained with a personal tenacity that the machine's manufacturer would have found both flattering and alarming.\nThe finished product was not beautiful. The covers were slightly irregular. The binding was functional, not elegant. The pages were of varying thicknesses because they came from different original notebooks.\nBut they were blank.\nCompletely, fully, usably blank.\nAnd blank pages, Fatima had learned over seven years of this work, were not a small thing.\nBlank pages were the space in which learning happened.\nThe notebook that had been Aryan's economics notebook \u2014 141 blank pages, good thick paper, grid-pattern on a slightly cream ground \u2014 was cut apart, sorted, and came out on the other side as two notebooks of 68 and 70 pages respectively. The slight thickness of the paper meant the binding held cleanly. The grid, lightly printed, was still visible on every page \u2014 faint guide lines that, as it turned out, would matter very much to the girl who received one of them.\n________________\n\n\nIV. Travelled\nThe delivery run to Osmanabad district happened in the third week of April.\nIt was a six-hour drive from Mumbai in a borrowed Bolero, loaded with 340 rebound notebooks, 180 pens, 40 geometry boxes, and 12 boxes of chalk \u2014 the latter a direct request from a headmaster who had been writing the day's lesson on a blackboard with the broken stubs of chalk for three months.\nThe volunteer driving was a software engineer named Dhruv who used his two annual leaves for Doosra Mauka runs. He was twenty-six, originally from Aurangabad, and had a particular feeling about this district \u2014 his grandmother had taught in a government school here for thirty years, and he had grown up with her stories of what schools in this part of Maharashtra needed and consistently did not have.\nHe delivered 68 notebooks to Zilla Parishad Prathamik Shala, Wadgaon \u2014 a government primary and upper primary school with 214 students, four permanent teachers, a compound wall, a functioning hand pump, a library with 40 books, and one functioning computer that lived in the headmaster's office.\nThe headmaster signed the receipt.\nThe notebooks were stacked in the storage room.\nThe next morning, they were distributed.\n________________\n\n\nV. Received\nPriya was thirteen years old and in Class 8.\nShe sat in the third row \u2014 not the front, because the front was where the loud and confident children sat and Priya was neither of those things, not loudly anyway \u2014 and she received her notebook the way she received all things that were given to her at school.\nWith both hands.\nHer grandmother had told her to always receive things with both hands. It shows the giver that you understand the weight of what they're giving you. Priya had been doing it since she was five and no longer thought about it. It was simply the only way to receive something.\nShe looked at the notebook.\nThe cover was cream card. On the front, in simple blue stamp ink, was the Doosra Mauka logo \u2014 two curved arrows forming a circle \u2014 and the words Doosra Mauka: Tujhyasaathi \u2014 For You.\nShe opened it.\nThe pages were thick. Thicker than the government-issue notebooks she usually got, which had a slight translucence that showed whatever was written on the other side. These pages were opaque. Solid. Each one had a very faint grid \u2014 not lines, a grid \u2014 in a light grey that was barely visible until you looked for it.\nShe ran her thumb across a page.\nShe felt the texture of good paper under her thumb in a way that is difficult to describe but that anyone who has ever held a quality notebook will understand immediately.\nShe did not know it had cost \u20b9480 in a mall in Bandra. She did not know it had sat in a bottom drawer for four months. She did not know about Salim Chacha or Meena Didi or Fatima's binding machine or Dhruv and his grandmother.\nShe knew that the pages were blank and thick and gridded.\nAnd she knew, with the particular certainty that comes to children who have been waiting for something without quite admitting it to themselves, exactly what she was going to use them for.\n________________\n\n\nVI. Used\nThere was one computer in the school.\nIt lived in the headmaster's office. Students could use it on Friday afternoons, in groups of four, for thirty minutes at a time. The computer ran Windows 7. It had no internet. It had a folder of offline educational software \u2014 basic mathematics, English vocabulary, a typing practice programme \u2014 installed by a government digital literacy initiative in 2019 that had provided the computer and the software and then, as these things go, not much else.\nPriya's class had been introduced to the computer in Class 6. She had typed her name. She had played the typing game. She had opened the folder called Programming Basics almost by accident one Friday and found a series of text files that were, she gradually understood, an introduction to something called Python.\nThe text files had been written by someone, somewhere, who had cared about being clear. They had simple explanations. They had examples. They had, at the end of each section, small exercises.\nWrite a programme that prints your name five times. Write a programme that adds two numbers. Write a programme that counts from 1 to 10.\nThere was no way to run programmes on this computer \u2014 the Python interpreter was not installed. There was no internet to install it. There was no teacher in the school who knew what Python was.\nBut there was the text file. And there were the exercises.\nAnd Priya had understood, slowly and then all at once, that the logic of the exercises was not dependent on running them. You could write them. You could trace through them with your finger, line by line, and follow what the computer would do if you could run them. You could make errors on paper and fix them on paper and understand on paper what made a programme correct.\nShe had been doing this in the margins of her mathematics notebook for four months.\nThe margins were very small.\n________________\n\n\nShe opened the new notebook on the first night after it was distributed.\nShe wrote at the top of the first page, in her careful, small handwriting:\nPython. Priya Kale. Class 8. 2026.\nBelow it, she wrote the first programme she had memorised from the text file.\nprint(\"Hello\")\nprint(\"Hello\")\nprint(\"Hello\")\nprint(\"Hello\")\nprint(\"Hello\")\n\n\nShe looked at it for a long time.\nThen she wrote below it, in a box she drew with the grid lines as her guide:\nThis prints \"Hello\" five times. The print() function sends text to the screen. The text must be inside quotation marks. Each print() is a separate instruction.\nShe drew a small arrow connecting the explanation to the code.\nShe turned the page.\nShe wrote the next programme.\nThe grid made everything align. The columns of code sat straight and readable in a way they had never managed in the margins of her mathematics notebook. She could write four spaces of indentation \u2014 which the text file had told her was important, was not optional, was the thing that told Python what was inside a loop \u2014 and it was exactly four spaces, no more, no less, because the grid was her guide.\nShe wrote until her mother called her for dinner.\nShe came back after dinner and wrote until the light was too low.\n________________\n\n\nVII. What the Notebook Became\nIn eleven months, Priya filled 64 of the 68 pages.\nShe wrote every programme from the text files \u2014 the simple ones, then the conditional statements, then the loops, then the functions. She invented her own variations. She made deliberate errors and annotated them in red pen \u2014 this doesn't work because \u2014 and then wrote the correction.\nShe created a personal syntax reference on pages 61 through 64. Keywords. Common functions. Rules she had learned by tracing through enough examples to understand why they were rules.\nShe had never run a single programme on a computer.\nBut she had written them until she understood them the way you understand something you have built by hand \u2014 not as information, but as a language.\n________________\n\n\nIn Class 9, a technology NGO brought six tablets to her school as part of a digital learning initiative. The tablets had Python installed through an offline educational app.\nThe teacher asked if anyone had used Python before.\nPriya raised her hand.\nThe teacher, who was young and genuinely curious about this, asked her to come to the front.\nShe wrote a function on the board \u2014 a simple one, from memory, correctly indented \u2014 and explained what it did.\nThe class was quiet.\nThe teacher stared at the board for a moment.\n\"Where did you learn this?\" he asked.\nShe thought about it.\n\"From a text file,\" she said. \"And a notebook.\"\n________________\n\n\nVIII. The Weight of a Blank Page\nAryan Mehta is in his second year of engineering college in Pune now.\nHe uses a notes app on his iPad. He has not bought a paper notebook in two years.\nHe does not know about Priya Kale. He never will.\nHe does not know that the notebook he left in a pile outside his building gate on a March morning travelled 470 kilometres south-east and became something so different from what he used it for that it might as well have been a different object entirely.\nHe does not know that 141 blank pages \u2014 the pages he never needed, the pages that were wasted to him simply by remaining empty \u2014 were exactly, precisely, the resource another child needed to learn something nobody in her school could teach her.\nHe does not need to know.\nThe giving did not require his awareness. It only required that the paper not be destroyed.\nIt required Salim Chacha's eye for things. Meena Didi's second shelf. Fatima's belief that blank pages were not a small thing. Dhruv's annual leave. A headmaster who signed a receipt. A girl who received something with both hands.\nIt required \u2014 somewhere in the middle of that chain \u2014 someone to understand that the difference between waste and resource is not the object itself.\nIt is only the distance between where it is and where it is needed.\n________________\n\n\nA Note From CauseKind\nThis story is fictional. The chain it describes is not.\nAcross India, every day, objects that have completed their usefulness for one person sit waiting for a path to the person for whom they have not yet begun to be useful. The gap between those two people is not insurmountable. It is not even particularly wide.\nIt is, most often, simply invisible.\nCauseKind's In-Kind platform is built to make it visible. To create the path that allows a notebook \u2014 or a bag, a phone, a uniform, a pack of books \u2014 to complete its journey from the person who has finished with it to the person who needs it to begin.\nPriya's story begins with a blank page.\nYours begins with whatever is sitting unused in your home right now.\n________________\n\n\nBrowse In-Kind Requests Near You \u2192 List Items You Want to Donate \u2192 Create Your Free CauseKind Account \u2192\n________________\n\n\nCauseKind is India's verified giving platform. Zero fees. Admin-verified listings. Every donation tracked to delivery. Give with purpose.\nContact us at support@causekind.org or +91 7719938619\n________________\n\n\nTags: notebook donation India, stationery donation India, CauseKind impact story, in-kind donation story India, rural education India, digital divide India, raddi-wala India, NGO notebook India, donate stationery India, girl education India, coding rural India, zero waste donation India": null}